Fourteen students died on Saturday morning in Toeni, Sourou province, in northwestern Burkina Faso when the bus transporting them jumped on a mine, Xinhua learned from a security source. “A bus transporting students to the city of Toma jumped on a mine. “The death toll is 14 and four injured,” an army official said on condition of anonymity to Xinhua. The reason for the incident was not immediately clear and further details had yet to emerge. An Islamist insurgency last year has ignited ethnic and religious tensions in Burkina Faso, especially in northern areas bordering Mali. On Dec. 1, 2019, 14 people were shot dead in an attack on a church in eastern Burkina Faso. On Nov. 6, 2019, gunmen opened fire on a convoy of buses carrying mine workers in the country’s East region, killing 39. (Xinhua) Vanguard News Nigeria The post 14 students killed in northwestern Burkina Faso appeared first on Vanguard News. Source: Vanguard Fourteen students died on Saturday morning in Toeni, Sourou province, in northwestern Burkina Faso when the bus transporting them jumped on a mine, Xinhua learned from a security source. The post 14 students killed in northwestern Burkina Faso appeared first on The Guardian Nigeria News - Nigeria and World News.… January 4, 2020 In "News" Former Toronto teacher and Montreal-based volunteer killed in Burkina Faso attack  CBC.caFirst picture of "exceptional" pregnant newlywed Cambridge student and husband killed in Burkina Faso terror attack  Mirror.co.ukEighteen shot dead in suspected jihadist attack on Burkina Faso restaurant  New York Daily NewsCanadian killed in Burkina Faso attack was a pregnant newlywed  TheSpec.comFull coverage Read… August 15, 2017 In "World" Canadians killed in Burkina Faso remembered for wanting to bring change  National PostTragedy as pregnant Cambridge student named as victim of terror shooting  Daily StarThe Burkina Faso-Mali attacks show the limits of the France-backed Sahel security strategy  QuartzCanadian killed in Bu